
To run and see the result/display

To create express project:
    npm init -y
    npm install express
or
npx express-generator myapp
cd myapp
npm install


1 To set up and run react:  modern
npm create vite@latest <directory name> >-- --template react
cd frontend
npm install
npm run dev


2 create-react-app (CRA), less modern
Command:
npx create-react-app student-frontend
cd student-frontend
npm start

Open browser at http://localhost:3000/
Replace code in App.js with your components → you’ll see output live.


axios.get('http://localhost:5000/')



To create and use next.js:
    npx create-next-app@latest my-next-app
    cd my-next-app
    npm run dev
    Open browser at http://localhost:3000/

    Edit pages/index.js → your changes appear live.



Can I use Next.js for backend, and how?

Yes! Next.js is fullstack:

Frontend: Components, JSX, React, pages.

Backend: API routes → act like server endpoints.

Example API route:

my-next-app/pages/api/hello.js

export default function handler(req, res) {
  res.status(200).json({ message: "Hello from backend!" });
}


Then, in frontend:

fetch('/api/hello')
  .then(res => res.json())
  .then(data => console.log(data.message));


How it works:

pages/api/* files are treated as serverless functions.

Can handle GET, POST, etc., like a mini backend.

✅ This is why Next.js is called fullstack React framework.